subject: pseq: Add base and UCD90320 device monitor classes
commitMessage:
pseq: Add base and UCD90320 device monitor classes

Add a power sequencer device monitoring base class and a UCD90320
subclass. Update power controller class to construct and pass device
information to device class.  Update build file to support.

Signed-off-by: Jim Wright <jlwright@us.ibm.com>
Change-Id: Idf3ef53011b23f15841d93795f9f0995892b10b9

Why?

https://github.com/openbmc/docs/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md#formatting-commit-messages
I can't think of anything more insightful than because the application needs command line arguments.
Perhaps an explanation of what arguments you plan to be looking for, and when one might use them?
Nit: Spelling
Done
Is this needed, or can you specify CLI::IsMember() directly?  Same question on line 36.
Done

In OpenBMC they prefer not to use the explicitly sized integers unless required for hardware interaction.  We are supposed to use size_t or int instead.

So maybe 'unsigned int' or 'unsigned long' here?

See https://github.com/openbmc/docs/blob/master/cpp-style-and-conventions.md#misc-guidelines
Done

I wouldn't suppose you are considering also having this app control the power sequencer, instead of just monitoring it?  Then it could also provide the pgood state and power on d-bus properties, and we could get rid of the old skeleton power control code for once and for all.

To get started down that direction, this would need to just start at multi-user.target and so wouldn't need any command line args.

I'm guessing you aren't :)  But doing it all in this app would save us from having to make two apps in the long run.

I hadn't thought of a combined app.  I had thought of replacing the skeleton app with a new app in this repository.  I think the combined app is the better idea.  Talked with Derek about this and he agreed.  I'll put this review in WIP for now.
This must be declared virtual.  Otherwise the correct destructor won't be run when the object is deleted via a PowerSequencerMonitor pointer.
Done
This should be declared virtual.  I think as long as it is virtual in the base class it is automatically virtual in the child class, but I think it is still good documentation.
Done
I think I2C only supports 7 and 10 bit addresses, so this comment is confusing.  Maybe this is something specific to that driver?
Done
This would probably be better as a DEBUG trace, since it's just printing data that is hardcoded in entity manager.
Done
Probably something worthy as a later enhancement, but how do you know this should be a UCD90320Monitor type? Should type be something you get from D-Bus as well?

Right, good point.  Right now I'm only looking for a specific UCD90320 interface, but in the future when I'm looking for multiple device type interfaces, I'll need to match on the name to create the correct device subclass.
Ooo! Fancy... odd formatting, but probably a complaint to take up with clang-format.

I hate the formatting, but our robots insist:
https://jenkins.openbmc.org/job/ci-repository/30833/ : FAILURE

This is a different result than when I run clang-format locally.  Is one or the other out of date?
